## Editorial Voice & Copy Rules

### Tone
Direct. Specific. Warm. Punchy. Local first.
Write like a smart neighbor, not a journalist trying to sound neutral.

### NEVER use these words/phrases
- vibrant
- nestled
- hidden gem
- world-class
- charming
- bustling
- community-driven
- at the end of the day
- in today's world
- It's worth noting
- Dive in
- Em dashes (—) in headlines
- "All Things Gwinnett is proud to..."

### Headline rules
- Specific over vague: "Duluth gets a 14-table izakaya" not "New restaurant opens"
- Active voice always
- Numbers over words: "14 stops" not "fourteen stops"
- No question headlines
- No "Here's why" or "This is why"

### Deck/subhead rules
- One sentence, max two
- Should add information the headline doesn't have
- Georgia serif, italic feel — conversational not formal

### Story tag naming
```
Food & drink  (not "Food", not "Eats")
Roads & traffic
Development
Crime & safety
Schools
Community
Business
Events
```

